as soon as the athletics were over, The families 
would all join together with a section, and then

08:06.419 --> 08:15.952
they'd have hamburgers or cook something, and 
beer, and soft drinks.

08:18.795 --> 08:22.380
Have a big get-together, then we'd have dining in, 
so the wives would all come to those. Normal

08:24.303 --> 08:25.204
clothes.

08:32.170 --> 08:45.124
We had

08:32.170 --> 08:45.124
a big awards night, and all the wives attended. We 
had graduation ceremonies. We did a whole part of

08:46.966 --> 08:47.707
that. And your wife, because you were a 
commandant, was she sort of formally in charge of

08:47.727 --> 08:57.677
the wives who were the instructors and the 
students? Yeah. And in these, or is... Did you or

08:58.985 --> 09:02.571
your wife ever have an opportunity to learn 
Portuguese? Yes, we both did. Oh, did you? Oh,

09:05.896 --> 09:06.076
yeah. When I left. Because I noticed you don't have 
a school here for Portuguese. Usually they have a

09:09.301 --> 09:10.423
school. Well, we

09:10.483 --> 09:16.192
attended school there on the base.

09:20.519 --> 09:20.659
Mm-hmm. One afternoon a week, every week.

09:26.035 --> 09:32.124
I even gave my farewell address in Portuguese. I 
don't know if he understood the word because it all

09:32.144 --> 09:36.870
collapsed.

09:38.292 --> 09:43.700
And then the Air Attaché said he

09:38.292 --> 09:43.700
could understand it. Vince Bennett, the Air 
Attaché, is a guy we worked through as an

09:43.720 --> 09:51.030
ambassador.

09:54.453 --> 09:58.778
He would come over and meet with us periodically. 
What do you think of the quality of the Portuguese

09:58.798 --> 10:08.368
Air Force

09:58.798 --> 10:08.368
and the officers that you have? The officers were 
very impressive, Portuguese officers. Very

10:11.551 --> 10:17.338
proud people.

10:17.358 --> 10:21.422
They don't take time in the criticism because they 
are so proud. So

10:22.465 --> 10:46.651
you never saw a pal on the back of it. We got to be very 
close friends. And he did this here in the States.

10:48.053 --> 10:48.273
No kidding. So we've been back. And they had the 
takeover over there by the socialists. He was

10:49.815 --> 10:50.295
forced to retire. He's

10:51.963 --> 11:16.395
gotten back in since then. He's been doing certain 
jobs for the Air Force. And he's trying to get

11:17.376 --> 11:17.957
there. His retirement reversed, but I don't think 
he will. He may have been present with me, but he's

11:19.018 --> 11:20.340
very bitter towards me. I don't know.

11:25.966 --> 11:28.591
He thinks you're back to normal. Yeah, it seems 
that way.

11:32.858 --> 11:37.346
What were your feelings in here about the 
revolution?

11:37.626 --> 11:44.478
It scared

11:37.626 --> 11:44.478
me. The chance of confidence didn't end. But I

11:49.321 --> 12:03.854
don't think the Portuguese are ready for it. 
They're

12:03.874 --> 12:07.938
just not the type. I

12:07.958 --> 12:11.441
don't believe it. What do you mean

12:11.461 --> 12:15.285
they're not the type? They're too individual. 
They're not going to submit to that type of regime.

12:17.046 --> 12:17.427
I don't believe it. They're more used to it. Almost 
dictatorship.

12:26.946 --> 12:40.326
We were more liable

12:26.946 --> 12:40.326
to go for

12:26.946 --> 12:40.326
that side. Very conservative. But Salazar is 
still in? No, Salazar is in. Well, I know, but was he

12:44.872 --> 12:46.475
in when you were there? Oh, yeah. Yeah, that's what 
I meant. And Salazar. Did you have an opportunity

12:51.691 --> 12:54.053
to meet him? What did you think of him? Very 
impressive person. Very. In what way?

13:05.165 --> 13:09.269
He seemed to have command of himself and 
everything. Very sure of himself.

13:17.498 --> 13:21.242
I thought he was doing what was best for the 
country, really. The feeling it gave me was that he

13:21.509 --> 13:39.500
was doing what he thought was best for

13:21.509 --> 13:39.500
the country

13:21.509 --> 13:39.500
all the time. He was not an opportunist. Was he 
friendly with the Americans?

13:45.530 --> 13:47.093
I don't think we'd been there if we weren't. Yeah.

13:51.985 --> 13:56.412
Well, let's stop right here for a minute, okay? Is 
there anything else about the Azores that we

13:56.432 --> 14:00.900
should discuss?

14:16.946 --> 14:17.807
No, I don't think so. Well, you had a real quick next 
assignment, Vice Commander, 12th Air Force Base

14:18.158 --> 14:29.609
at Bergstrom, which only lasted from October 69 to 
May 1970. Why was it so brief? Usually, what's

14:31.090 --> 14:33.612
that, a two-year job? Well, you have no set tours as 
a general officer. You just go when they say and do

14:36.835 --> 14:46.444
what they say, and

14:36.835 --> 14:46.444
your life's not your own. I think they needed 
somebody over in Vietnam in a hurry, because

14:46.660 --> 14:56.053
somebody finished up or something, and I went over 
to finish up the tour. I was happy to get the

14:56.093 --> 15:00.359
opportunity. At Bergstrom,

15:02.682 --> 15:11.554
was it basically a question of hearing, by this 
time, We were training pilots. Our major thrust

15:16.127 --> 15:23.835
was training pilots for replacement pilots to go 
to Vietnam, yes. Now, because of the difference in

15:25.798 --> 15:39.313
that type of war, the jungle warfare versus the 
regular World War II or Korean War, was there a

15:25.798 --> 15:39.313
different emphasis on training?

15:42.922 --> 15:52.832
Well, the emphasis was making them combat-ready 
in the aircraft to perform the missions that the

15:42.922 --> 15:52.832
aircraft was capable of performing. And then when 
they went to Vietnam, they were prepared to do

15:53.953 --> 15:58.237
whatever was required. They could do any mission 
that was required in their particular aircraft.

16:04.764 --> 16:10.009
And most of these aircrafts, of course, were the 
jet aircrafts, even though we did use prop planes.

16:10.029 --> 16:11.190
By that time, they were all. The Vietnamese had the 
props then. One thing about Vietnam was, of

16:14.797 --> 16:20.443
course, the SAM missiles. Did you train them to 
attempt to evade SAMs? Well, you had evasion

16:28.310 --> 16:32.314
tactics, yes, that you taught them. They were 
given all the tactics for SAM evasion, what to do,

16:32.975 --> 16:38.660
and so forth. What were they told to do? They had all 
different. It depends on the situation. And if

16:45.798 --> 16:50.686
they knew that SAMs were firing, well, they took 
evasive tactics. And they were able to maneuver so

16:51.748 --> 16:59.180
that they would not be intercepted. Quite a few, of 
course, during 67 and 68, when they put SAMs in

16:59.200 --> 17:07.833
North Vietnam, quite a few of our fighter pilots 
were shot down. How was morale? Well, morale

17:09.811 --> 17:12.274
wasn't... The morale when I was there was good. 
Now, I'm not sure about how it was back when several

17:14.596 --> 17:20.182
of them were getting shot down. But we had 
perfected electronic countermeasures so that we

17:21.223 --> 17:38.322
knew when they were launched and we knew more about 
where they were because we had ECM aircraft go with

17:21.223 --> 17:38.322
the strikes, especially those in the north that 
not. They all had As well as all the B-52 missions,

17:40.118 --> 17:44.703
too. And the training back at Bergstrom was a lot of 
new technology? Not a gross amount of new

17:50.929 --> 17:52.811
technology. The training at Bergstrom itself was 
only for the RF-4, and that was only for the

17:52.851 --> 17:59.037
reconnaissance. So we had the other bases at Luke 
and Nellis and George and

17:59.057 --> 18:08.387
I don't remember. We had several other bases where 
we were training people on different types of

18:09.177 --> 18:16.344
aircraft. Now, when you got to Bergson, did you 
apply for Vietnam? When you get to be a general

18:20.389 --> 18:22.611
officer, you don't apply for anything. But you 
must have friends and said, gee, I sure would like

18:23.892 --> 18:27.376
to get to Vietnam. I mean, did you tell anybody that 
you wanted to get over there because you were next

18:27.436 --> 18:36.045
to her duty in June of 1970?

18:39.299 --> 18:40.180
It was in Vietnam. Yeah. I was happy to go. I wanted 
to go. As

18:46.365 --> 18:52.371
I said before, when you get to be a general officer, 
you don't ask questions. You just go where you're

18:52.411 --> 18:56.154
told, and if somebody wants you, they'll call for 
you. If they don't, they won't. Okay. Now... You

18:59.197 --> 19:02.079
have no choice in the matter. Right. You were at Tan 
Sonot for the 7th Air Force And you were in

19:09.083 --> 19:13.367
operations. Yeah. What exactly was your job? The 
job was to direct all the operations of the

19:16.369 --> 19:28.880
different organizations

19:16.369 --> 19:28.880
that were under Seventh Air Force. I wrote all the 
ops orders, tell them what to do, and coordinated

19:29.020 --> 19:38.888
with intelligence to send out that information. 
and

19:39.543 --> 20:08.503
directed the reconnaissance missions to fulfill 
the intelligence requirements, and

19:39.543 --> 20:08.503
evaluated the performance of the units below, and

19:39.543 --> 20:08.503
evaluated requirements of what was going to be 
needed in the future for whatever program that we

19:39.543 --> 20:08.503
had, whatever our program was going to be. in the 
ongoing year and

20:08.973 --> 20:36.217
provide the command and the control for the 
direction of the commander to direct the

20:08.973 --> 20:36.217
operation. Now, when you were down there, Was it 
the responsibility of the 7th Air Force,

20:39.331 --> 20:44.638
basically that core area? No, the responsibility 
of the 7th Air Force was the responsibility for the

20:45.680 --> 20:50.927
whole. For the whole Vietnamese theater, but not 
including Thailand. Including Thailand.

20:56.174 --> 20:57.155
Including Thailand. Including Thailand. 
They're everything in Southeast Asia. Okay, and

21:01.140 --> 21:02.302
Okinawa? No, not Okinawa. So who controlled the 
B-52s? The B-52s were, we controlled the B-52s,

21:09.149 --> 21:13.455
their strikes. But we only had operational 
control over them. Right. Then you went back to

21:19.042 --> 21:21.406
Okinawa. Yeah. Okay. This war, of course, has been 
debated by historians now for a long time, and was

21:25.631 --> 21:38.008
debated by the public at large for a few years, 
especially when you were there. And I'd like to ask

21:39.254 --> 21:42.958
you some questions about that war. How did you feel 
that we were getting along with the South

21:43.459 --> 21:48.285
Vietnamese? Well, we were getting along with the 
South Vietnamese Air Force fairly well, but I

21:49.906 --> 21:57.796
don't think we were getting along too well with the 
South Vietnamese people. I think it was a dirty,

21:58.857 --> 22:00.579
rotten mess. It was a no-win war, which is 
ridiculous. The situation that we put our forces

22:05.512 --> 22:14.603
in, we put our people in, was almost inexcusable. I 
just can't see anybody wanting to put the United

22:14.623 --> 22:19.649
States of America in that sort of condition. Why 
don't you elaborate on that? Well, when you get in a

22:22.192 --> 22:35.367
no-win situation and the President of the United 
States has to direct a squadron what it can do, then

22:22.192 --> 22:35.367
something is wrong.

22:35.735 --> 22:56.101
When you tie the hands of your strike force that 
could have ended the war in the very beginning, in a

22:35.735 --> 22:56.101
short period of time, and you tie their hands so 
completely that all they can do is what they're

22:35.735 --> 22:56.101
told they can do that day by the President of the 
United States, then there's something lacking.

22:56.121 --> 22:57.843
And we never will win one like that. That's the 
second no-win thing we've been through. And there

23:02.469 --> 23:04.071
was no excuse to be in the mother. And Korea was bad 
enough, but this Vietnam thing is ridiculous.

23:10.733 --> 23:12.415
It's just a dirty, rotten mess. That's all I can 
say. Okay, now tell me about, give me a specific

23:13.677 --> 23:19.365
example of this no-win situation.

23:23.690 --> 23:26.454
We weren't allowed to bomb in North Vietnam. When I 
first got there, we couldn't bomb in North

23:27.676 --> 23:30.820
Vietnam. We had to get permission. It was directed 
down from above what targets would it hit. So the

23:40.037 --> 23:43.081
Pentagon and the White House controlled... It was 
in the White House. So the White House controlled

23:44.542 --> 23:50.409
the targeting. And that must have caused a lot of 
resentment in Saigon. It did. It caused

23:57.478 --> 23:59.320
resentment everywhere.

24:02.742 --> 24:06.305
And I think Mr. Kennedy could have stopped it from 
the very beginning. So if you don't withdraw

24:06.325 --> 24:08.967
those, we're going to do this tomorrow. We're 
going to bomb this factory or this place or this

24:09.468 --> 24:14.813
place and then go up and do it. And if we displayed 
some power at the very beginning, rather than

24:16.194 --> 24:28.544
keeping completely hands off, there never would 
have been a war in South Korea. They've been

24:28.564 --> 24:31.267
stopped in North Vietnam. We did the same thing in 
Korea. We stopped at the Yalu River. We didn't go

24:35.410 --> 24:37.853
across the Yalu River. So the Chinese came in and 
wiped us out. So as far as China now for a second, did

24:41.136 --> 24:52.488
you agree with John MacArthur as far as we should 
have been bombing north of the Yalu? Yes, I did. Of

24:54.530 --> 24:58.995
course, I don't disagree with President Truman 
firing because President Truman was the boss. And

24:59.756 --> 25:02.719
if the boss says do that, you do it. If you look in 
retrospect, everybody can look back and see what

25:03.138 --> 25:08.085
would have been better and what wouldn't. Most of 
them can. But in my opinion, we would have been a lot

25:11.009 --> 25:15.135
better off if we had gone ahead. They never would 
have come in, in all probability.

25:23.487 --> 25:28.814
Did you sense a lot of resentment in Saigon with 
your superiors? Who was your superior, by the way?

25:30.256 --> 25:33.060
Well, George Brown, who was later chairman of the 
Joint Chiefs of Staff, What

25:33.412 --> 25:38.618
are his feelings?

25:41.862 --> 25:44.705
I believe he felt the same way, and General Abrams 
did too.

25:49.791 --> 25:58.320
And most of the Air Force, the senior Air Force 
people that I knew felt that way, in my opinion. Of

25:58.340 --> 26:02.305
course, I can't speak for them, but that's the way I 
felt they thought. Now, you made an earlier

26:02.639 --> 26:12.609
statement that we got along all right with the Air 
Force Vietnamese people, but we didn't get along

26:02.639 --> 26:12.609
all right with the civilian population. Could you 
elaborate on that? Well, I don't know what

26:15.511 --> 26:22.638
question of getting along with them, just the 
stories that were told me about encounters with

26:15.511 --> 26:22.638
them. And the Vietnamese people didn't want us 
there, I didn't think. How'd you know? Out in the

26:28.564 --> 26:31.667
boondocks, the people out in the boondocks.

26:34.634 --> 26:36.496
They wanted everybody to go away and leave them 
alone. That was the feeling that you got. That's

26:39.519 --> 26:41.601
the feeling I had. Now, in the... Did you have any 
examples? I mean, did you have any good things to

26:44.884 --> 26:46.585
tell you then? I had a chaplain who was in the field 
with the airborne division tell me that that's

26:48.968 --> 27:03.021
where I got the feeling, the expression of that 
feeling from him, that he got that feeling.

27:07.692 --> 27:33.653
I guess the Vietnamese had been under the French 
and under domination for so long that they were

27:07.692 --> 27:33.653
happy to be away from that, and yet they don't want 
North Vietnam

27:07.692 --> 27:33.653
taking them over.

27:33.733 --> 27:34.234
We were there. We prolonged the war. by being 
there. Or we could have, if we had done it right in

27:39.853 --> 27:47.282
the beginning, they would never have had a chance 
to come in, in my opinion.

27:50.325 --> 27:52.147
What were the conditions like at Pan Snow? As far as 
the Americans were concerned, they were fine.

27:59.996 --> 28:04.902
Comfortable quarters, good flying conditions. 
good facilities, good runways, good radar

28:06.485 --> 28:13.835
control. We've got a good system there, a good 
tactical control

28:15.037 --> 28:26.432
system to take care of the strikes, monitoring. 
How effective do you think that the Air Force was in

28:27.594 --> 28:35.365
Vietnam as far as destroying the enemy? I mean, on 
the missions. Regardless of what the politicians

28:36.607 --> 28:43.815
controlled or which ones you could bomb, et 
cetera, how about the ones that you could? How

28:43.975 --> 28:45.316
effective were they? I think they were quite 
effective. I don't think there's any question

28:46.658 --> 28:50.522
about it. They were very effective. We were able to 
hit the targets. And if the intelligence was good,

28:55.868 --> 28:59.852
we clobbered whatever was there.

29:02.655 --> 29:05.078
But when you can't see through the jungle, We have 
an impossible problem almost. Yeah. To even

29:09.664 --> 29:13.530
assess your game. Sure.

29:16.655 --> 29:24.647
That is a problem, and of course we bombed the Ho Chi 
Minh Trail to death almost, and we still didn't

29:16.655 --> 29:24.647
stop the flow of supply. I'm surprised. Is that 
correct? That's correct. Why not? I don't know. I

29:31.577 --> 29:33.360
really don't know. We may have stopped the flow, 
but they already had so many down there, they

29:34.167 --> 29:37.331
didn't need them. And give them time enough to 
repair and get through. And don't ever think we

29:43.078 --> 29:49.406
didn't bomb it. We bombed the hell out of it. Looked 
like the moon.

29:58.858 --> 30:02.402
What about the Debolian campaign of the ranch 
hands? as part of the Air Force. Is that also under

30:04.067 --> 30:09.854
your control?

