This, of course, has come into the news lately, 
Agent Orange, and if that is going to have an impact

30:09.874 --> 30:23.072
on the people who were sprayed, et cetera. And I was 
wondering about your ideas of the use of the

30:23.873 --> 30:28.980
deployments.

30:35.137 --> 30:44.527
Well, I'm not

30:35.137 --> 30:44.527
too sure in my own mind how effective it was. Some 
people think it was quite effective. And others,

30:48.931 --> 30:51.474
like me, they're not quite so sure.

30:55.638 --> 30:56.599
It had some effect. I know that. But to be worth all 
the effort it took, I don't know whether it was

30:58.221 --> 31:05.008
worth it or not. I

31:06.575 --> 31:15.785
just wasn't in a position to evaluate it, really.

31:19.689 --> 31:22.292
What did you think of General Brown? What's your 
opinion on him? He was fine. Fine. Fine,

31:26.597 --> 31:29.941
outstanding soldier. A real professional 
soldier.

31:34.345 --> 31:35.907
How'd you get along with him? What kind of man is he? 
Is he easy along with ours? Is he demanding? No,

31:40.172 --> 31:43.237
he's fairly demanding, but not overly so. He just 
wanted you to do your job.

32:01.562 --> 32:06.349
He was very fair and knew what he wanted. sure of 
himself.

32:13.482 --> 32:17.806
He still was very pleasant to me, and will remain in 
any way.

32:20.948 --> 32:23.951
How'd you, did you, did you know General Abrams? 
Yes. Probably worked pretty close on, on

32:25.412 --> 32:28.195
something. Worked, well I went to his staff 
meeting every week. Yeah. And uh. How was he? He,

32:34.300 --> 32:38.344
he's a, he was a crusty old soldier. of the old 
school. I admired him. Why? I thought he was a great

32:42.518 --> 32:50.270
American.

32:50.290 --> 32:52.293
He was very thoughtful of his men.

32:57.041 --> 33:06.255
He took advantage of every bit of intelligence 
that he could get, and he tried in every way to win

32:57.041 --> 33:06.255
the war.

33:07.838 --> 33:19.212
supportive of the Air Force and their mission, and

33:07.838 --> 33:19.212
the Navy as well.

33:19.232 --> 33:24.900
He was, I think, just an outstanding commander, 
really. He had a grasp of the situation and knew

33:24.920 --> 33:35.093
what he was trying to do, and worked at it day and 
night. Hard working, man. I know he was.

33:40.002 --> 33:50.813
In general, then, it sounds to me that you have a 
very high opinion of the military leadership of

33:40.002 --> 33:50.813
the American Forces in Vietnam. I sure do. I sure 
do.

33:57.120 --> 33:58.101
How about on the other side? How about, let's talk 
about that. I know we talked a little bit about how

34:01.164 --> 34:03.647
you got along with the Vietnamese. Air Force 
people, but, you know, a lot of the blame, I heard a

34:04.201 --> 34:14.832
lot of blame put on the Vietnamese themselves for 
losing their own war, and I'm sure you've heard

34:04.201 --> 34:14.832
that. What's your opinion on that?

34:19.197 --> 34:23.442
Well, I think in a large part that might be true. I 
don't know whether they had any

34:23.462 --> 34:32.892
anything that brought them all together to really 
want to do something. I don't know whether

34:34.559 --> 34:40.407
I'd almost call them lethargic. They didn't want 
to talk about the peasants out in the field. They

34:43.171 --> 34:45.293
didn't know about all this other stuff going on. 
They just wanted everybody to leave and let them

34:45.834 --> 34:48.077
alone. That's the feeling and impression that I 
got from talking to people. And did you take, every

34:55.287 --> 34:59.633
once in a while, did you take trips out in the field? 
Yes, I went to every one of the bases. I flew

35:02.256 --> 35:02.997
missions. You actually were flying some 
missions? Yeah. What kind of aircraft? Well, I

35:08.927 --> 35:12.411
flew one in the F-100, and I flew one in the F-4. As a 
major general? Yeah. They had you fly in missions?

35:17.597 --> 35:20.700
Well, they let me fly missions. Oh, they let you. 
But isn't that unusual? I don't think so. I flew

35:25.125 --> 35:29.750
nine reconnaissance missions. But you didn't fly 
any combat, did you? No. Yes, I flew combat. You

35:35.275 --> 35:37.879
flew, like you flew into North Vietnam? Oh no, they 
were not letting me go into North Vietnam. I was

35:40.522 --> 35:42.124
thinking you would have been captured. I know it, 
that's North Vietnam. So I went on missions in

35:44.306 --> 35:50.193
Vietnam, where they were dive bombing missions. 
And you participated? Yes. I don't know, I just, to

35:54.398 --> 35:56.541
me. It seems incredible that they'd have a major 
general doing that, not only because of your rank,

35:57.685 --> 36:05.974
but also because of your age. What do you mean my 
age? I was combat qualified in the RF-4. Well, I

36:11.660 --> 36:22.611
know that you're combat qualified, but I was under 
the opinion that mostly on these you'd have the

36:11.660 --> 36:22.611
younger men doing these. You do, but you got to know 
something about it. I've always felt that the guy

36:26.913 --> 36:32.842
in charge ought to know something about what the 
guy is asking him to do, what he's asking him to do.

36:33.162 --> 36:33.663
He should know. Oh, yeah. But you went out in 
strafing and dive bombing missions? Yes. I wasn't

36:42.977 --> 36:43.938
doing it. I was in the back seat with a guy in the 
front. I ain't doing the actual firing.

36:56.444 --> 36:59.447
And that was typical for a major general? I don't 
know if it was typical or not. As I say, there were

37:02.850 --> 37:08.215
only three or four missions that I went on. And I 
flew the reconnaissance missions. I was taking

37:09.837 --> 37:10.658
pictures. I actually did those in Cambodia and 
South Vietnam, and also

37:10.678 --> 37:23.430
in Laos. Not with none, no. And what did you find out 
on these missions? What the problem was, when they

37:33.211 --> 37:46.527
were trying to find the tardy in the jungle, and 
even though you mark it, the forward air

37:33.211 --> 37:46.527
controller marks it with smoke, you don't see 
anything but leaves, trees. So you go down and hit

37:46.547 --> 37:51.473
the smoke and hope there was something there. 
Occasionally you get an explosion and know you hit

37:51.493 --> 37:53.856
something. Because you have no idea what you're 
bombing most of the time. You can't jump.

38:04.320 --> 38:07.345
Gee, that must have been really difficult to run 
bombing missions on a night down.

38:10.829 --> 38:11.410
Yes, it was. And difficult for the pilots. What do 
you think about the quality of our pilots over

38:15.296 --> 38:17.459
there? Outstanding. Oh, they were super. compare 
them to our fighter pilots in World War II? They

38:23.860 --> 38:27.445
were much better trained than we were when we got to 
combat in World War II. Really? Oh, yeah. They're

38:28.486 --> 38:29.627
experienced people. I mean, people, we got over 
there maybe with 300 hours of flying. They were

38:37.777 --> 38:41.262
there with 3,000 hours of flying. So there's all 
the difference in the world in the level of

38:41.282 --> 38:46.188
experience. And the machines were all 
complicated, too. Oh, absolutely. And more of

38:50.030 --> 38:53.613
technical, and more firepower. Everything has 
upgraded tremendously.

39:00.479 --> 39:01.259
How could you ever... I know one of the things that 
McNamara wanted to do was to sort of quantify the

39:01.580 --> 39:05.623
war. McNamara was stupid, in my opinion. Well, I 
want your opinion on McNamara. I want you to

39:12.008 --> 39:14.911
continue on that. I think he tried to quantify 
everything and put it in a computer, and you can't

39:14.931 --> 39:19.935
do that, in my opinion. And he wanted commonality 
in everything. And that slowed down the

39:23.855 --> 39:34.128
procurement of weapons because he wanted Air 
Force and Navy to have airplanes that were common

39:23.855 --> 39:34.128
to be the same thing. And he

39:35.270 --> 39:49.888
lost sight of the fact that you had to have these 
things now, not programmed in the future. like he

39:50.948 --> 39:52.089
was trying to do. And he squeezed down on

39:53.892 --> 40:17.783
the budget so that even though we were able to do 
some research and development, he squeezed it

39:53.892 --> 40:17.783
down so much that he cut out most of our research and 
development.

40:18.404 --> 40:21.527
to stay with the state of the art at this time rather 
than progress. Well, that's what I think he did. He

40:24.751 --> 40:27.814
stopped the progression in the state of the art.

40:31.438 --> 40:34.581
There's a lot of resentment in the knowledge area 
about Mackinac. Yes, there was. I guess there

40:36.683 --> 40:37.664
still is. I mean, there was Newman. Did you ever 
meet him? Oh, yes. When he came to Saigon? No, when

40:45.332 --> 40:48.175
he came to Maxwell.

40:51.108 --> 40:56.195
No, I didn't see him inside,

40:51.108 --> 40:56.195
no. When he came to, um, what's it, and you just came 
in to inspect, he talked to you? Oh, he talked to the

41:03.304 --> 41:06.328
War College, yeah.

41:13.698 --> 41:14.078
Yeah, okay. And, uh, usually we'd have a little 
dinner beforehand, and he invited the

41:14.099 --> 41:19.005
Commandants.

41:22.090 --> 41:25.976
For me.

41:25.996 --> 41:28.761
Were people friendly toward him? Oh, yeah. There 
was no

41:30.864 --> 41:37.054
dislike for the man personally. No, I don't think 
so. I don't recall any. You can dislike a man. I

41:44.706 --> 41:48.291
mean, not dislike a man personally, but you can 
dislike what he does. His policy was still like

41:48.311 --> 41:49.954
him, huh? I've got a lot of friends that I love, but I 
don't like some of the things they do.

41:59.783 --> 42:15.080
Now back to Vietnam, and did you ever receive a 
survey from a Brigadier General that served in

41:59.783 --> 42:15.080
Vietnam, and later wrote a book about it, and his 
name was Douglas Kennard? Kennard?

42:16.181 --> 42:20.346
D-I-N-N-A-R-D.

42:16.181 --> 42:20.346
Never did? He sent a survey out to, I guess there 
were 168 generals at one time or the other served in

42:22.570 --> 42:32.045
Vietnam. He sent a survey out to these people and 
asked them questions about why we lost the war and

42:32.065 --> 42:40.738
things like that. You

42:40.818 --> 42:48.430
never did receive any of those? No. At this time, 
you made, or right before that, you made Major

42:49.520 --> 42:53.465
General. Can you tell me about that?

43:01.213 --> 43:04.998
Just that I was eligible and got promoted. Well, 
you got promoted awfully quickly. Well, that's a

43:10.084 --> 43:11.726
lot easier. You only competed with a few people 
there.

43:19.810 --> 43:21.412
second star than it was the first? Sure. Less 
competition. A lot less.

43:28.822 --> 43:32.768
And was that part of filling the job in Vietnam? I 
mean, did you need two stars to do that job? Was it

43:36.793 --> 43:38.616
usually a two-star response going? Yeah. But I was 
promoted before I went. Yeah, I know that. Okay. I

43:45.746 --> 43:47.488
was wondering about Why did we lose the one in 
Vietnam? You alluded to some of this. I like your

43:53.682 --> 43:54.864
answer. Well, because the Air Force's hands were 
tied at the very beginning and they weren't

43:55.866 --> 44:17.256
allowed to go in and

43:55.866 --> 44:17.256
destroy the targets and the will to fight in North 
Vietnam at the very beginning when we had the

43:55.866 --> 44:17.256
capability, when we had the force there to do it, 
and we didn't do it. We could have had them at the

44:18.670 --> 44:26.078
negotiation table a long time ago if we'd started 
bombing North Vietnam even after it was

44:18.670 --> 44:26.078
authorized. That's the way we got them to the 
bargaining table. But we could have won the war

44:28.741 --> 44:34.908
before then without having to go to any bargaining 
table if we'd done just the same thing.

44:38.392 --> 44:42.477
So in other words... And our hands were tied, 
actually, when we were bombing North Vietnam. The

44:42.497 --> 44:45.961
specific targets were picked by the President. 
Sure. In other words, you blame politicians. I do.

44:51.371 --> 44:51.471
Okay.

44:55.417 --> 45:13.102
What about the question of

44:55.417 --> 45:13.102
reporting back to the Pentagon how successful you 
were in the armament of the body counts, which were

44:55.417 --> 45:13.102
not very accurate, according to the generals I 
talked to. You just talked earlier about shooting

45:17.581 --> 45:28.611
in the jungle, how could you, maybe you might see 
something explode, how could you tell what kind of

45:17.581 --> 45:28.611
damage you were doing if you were hitting the 
targets?

45:28.932 --> 45:30.353
Well, if you're in the jungle, you can.

45:34.517 --> 45:46.288
But we had other targets and we could see them and we 
could tell if we shot a truck up or...

45:34.517 --> 45:46.288
And we had other techniques, infrared sensors, 
and so forth. And we had smart bombs, too. They

45:51.551 --> 45:55.695
could hit whatever we pinpointed them on. We had a 
lot of success with that, smart bombs, infrared

45:55.715 --> 46:00.139
sensors.

46:06.305 --> 46:12.951
And when they located troops, we could put 
something on them.

46:14.230 --> 46:19.077
could at least rattle their eardrums and then hit 
them. One of the charges that was made by some

46:19.097 --> 46:31.615
people was that there was careerism in the 
military during the war, and that there was

46:31.949 --> 46:43.923
mandatory for an officer's career to get his tour 
of duty over there, but then the rotation was so

46:31.949 --> 46:43.923
fast that often they couldn't serve, often they 
couldn't do their job very well. For example, most

46:44.023 --> 46:51.632
jobs are rotated in six months, and you were there 
for six months, and it was the same situation.

46:51.652 --> 46:55.777
Could you learn that job in six months? Could you 
learn who your men were? Could you work

46:58.079 --> 47:00.302
efficiently?

47:03.320 --> 47:06.401
Well, I think that's too short a period. I really 
do.

